  "original_text": "madanaphala kalpa — emetic [vamana] preparations utilizing Madanaphala (Randia dumetorum) as the principal emetic drug [pradhana dravya]. The chapter enumerates twelve principal emetic substances [dvadasha vamana dravyani]: madanaphala, jimutaka, ikshvaku, dhamargava, kutaja, kritavedhana, shanka, koshaphanki, antahkotarapushpi, pratyakpushpa, shyamaka, and krutavedhana. Of these, madanaphala is declared supreme [uttama] for emesis. The fruit [phala], pericarp [phalatvak], flower [pushpa], root [mula], and seed [bija] of madanaphala are all employed. Preparations include: (1) phanta [hot infusion] of the pulp with honey [madhu] and rock salt [saindhava lavana]; (2) kalka [paste] of the pericarp mixed with vacha, saindhava, madhu, and warm water; (3) kvatha [decoction] combined with mulethi [yashtimadhu] and honey; (4) churna [powder] of dried fruit mixed with trikatu [pippali, maricha, shunthi] and administered with warm water; (5) medicated ghrita [ghee preparation] of madanaphala for patients of delicate constitution [sukumara]; (6) yoga [compound formula] with sauvarchala lavana and nimba bark for kapha-dominant disorders. The chapter specifies dose [matra] according to constitution [prakriti], season [rita], and strength of disease [vyadhi bala]. Emesis [vamana karma] is indicated for kapha disorders [kaphaja vyadhi], certain pitta conditions, poisoning [visha], skin diseases [kushtha], respiratory conditions [shvasa, kasa], nausea [hrillasa], and fever [jwara] of kapha origin. Contraindications [nishedha] include: the very elderly [ativridha], very young children [atibala], the extremely emaciated [atikrsha], pregnant women [garbhini], those with upward-moving vata disorders [udavarta], cardiac weakness [hridroga], and hemorrhagic conditions [raktapitta]. Post-emetic management [samsarjana krama] — graduated dietary reh
